<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by AppleKid on 04-30-2001 04:32 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL"> Speaking of that Halflife map, long before this incident I made a Doom map of my High School. And just like any home-grown Doom map there almost invariably had to be a cyberdemon in it. Mine was in the office.  :)
 (oh, and, when you boot your computer and it freezes on startup and you hear your hard drive click like a madman, letting it go for several hours is a bad idea... I can't hook an ATX power supply to a power timer, and that's a good thing with this hindsight)

 The problem is that everyone wants someone to blame. It's an extention of that "it could never happen to me" ... that is, "it could never happen to me so it must be someone else's fault." What really pisses me off is that for every one of these fucked up kids there's at least a dozen million others who play violent games that *shock* don't kill their neighbors. I mean, how many copies of Doom sold? And how many more were pirated?

 Some people need to learn that bad things happen. Murder is probably the oldest crime in human history, next to theft. Is it the parent's fault? Maybe. Everyone knows that the media spends more time showing footage of Quake and that video of the kid getting hit by a car by Jackass fans than looking into the murderer's life.

 Hell, if the kid was an accident, how about after the video game company suit they can sue the condom manufacturer.

(I'm thinking of a sig---
-----
Leauge of American Citizens that Aren't Complete Idiots)</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
